commit_message:
libvirt: saving the lxc rootfs device in instance metadata

Currently, nbd/loop device, to which lxc image has been
connected, is being saved as instance root device, which causing
the attached bug.
Saving the device name in instance system metadata instead.

Closes-Bug: #1330981
Change-Id: I3a0533a89ea8af61349118a39b822f4af146cc04

commit_message:
Add HA support to the l3 agent

This patch is a part of the blueprint l3-high-availability
Known To-Do:
- Clean up keepalived configuration files when an HA router
  is deleted
- Handle routes_updated via keepalived virtual_routes

Wishlist / Future Patches:
- conntrackd
- Report HA state (active / standby) for each HA router via API
- Add ability to migrate HA routers from network node by
  setting admin_state down on the l3 agent

Change-Id: I9f1e6dd41673fb67df2ce5b542087e7b678622ef
Implements: blueprint l3-high-availability
Co-Authored-By: Assaf Muller <amuller@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Change LOG.warn to LOG.debug in _shutdown_instance

Change LOG.warn to LOG.debug for detaching volume related exceptions
in _shutdown_instance in compute/manager.py, since as the log message
said the exceptions should be ignored. It's probably not worth a
warning in the log.

Change-Id: Ibe216b9bccf590e64aa1b966753bd1ec67c8dbdf

specific metadata whose schema was previously defined.

When one entity is a collection of another entity, the contained entity should have a read/write attribute to set/access the container, and the container entity should have a read-only attribute to access the entities it contains. Hi Nachi, responding to your questions:

Nachi: Could add more on error handling? What's happening when we delete referenced resources

Sumit: Yes, I have added a sentence to this effect.

Nachi: What's happing when there is no consumer/provider matches filters

Sumit: The ContractConsumerScope creation will fail if there is no matching Contract.

Nachi: Why we have consumer/provider even if we have a concept of "Role"?
  Consumers or providers are one of roles, right?

Sumit: The relationship captures more than just the Role. Firstly it captures the Contract ID that is being consumed. Secondly it provides a way to put a constraint on the EPGs that can be chosen to from the pool of EPGs that provide that particular Contract (this is being done via the scope attribute). Third is the Role of the consuming EPG in that relationship. Note that Scope and Role are optional and can be defaulted.'}, {'account_id': 10310, 'date': '2014-05-01 23:49:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 490, 'date': '2014-05-01 23:50:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Group-based Policy Blueprint

in Neutron.

commit_message:
Change the exception type for Storwize/SVC driver

When create a volume from snapshot or clone a volume,
Storwize/SVC require the same size for the source volume
and target, if not, will raise VolumeDriverException.

For this case, InvalidInput is more appropriate.

Change-Id: I4383c2eb8758077b3029b862dd8b6f982e1850a7

commit_message:
Cleanup network when reschedule instance even network_allocated isn't True

If any exception is raised before setting network_allocated to True in
system_metadata and after the network resources allocated, the compute
manager won't release those network resources. This patch make the code
cleanup network even network_allocated is't True.

Change-Id: I76f5ad3e08d8f4c85924a4d941072aa7037a2398

commit_message:
Make test_revoke expiry times distinct

Calling _future_time had the possibility of returning the same value
if it is called between clock ticks.  It appears to be happening in
gate, potentially due to being run in a VM.

Instead, for the loop that revokes distinct events,
Assign each a different expires_at time.

Conflicts:

	keystone/tests/test_revoke.py

Change-Id: Iab7ed92bb1e142651265a167ae73d6d1225b01a9
Closes-Bug: #1300581
(cherry picked from commit 5fbb0a28bc40d3e30b416a284cbe63f233cca39e)

commit_message:
Fix revoking a scoped token from an unscoped token

When a scoped token that was created from an unscoped token was
revoked, the original token wound up being revoked. This is because
the scope wasn't included in the revocation event. By including the
scope in the revocation event only the scoped token is revoked.

Change-Id: I5652663ab7e1176d3b1efc5d218a8a020498067e
Closes-Bug: #1347318
(cherry picked from commit da00da732d6be0626810fe4ec87d40dab16117de)

commit_message:
Fix revoking domain-scoped tokens

A token scoped to a domain wouldn't be revoked for a domain-wide
revocation event. This is because the code to convert a token to a
dict for revocation event processing didn't handle domain-scoped
tokens.

Partial-Bug: #1349597

Change-Id: Ib2c58f3fc8790dbe7f8b073d18d3fa9b0dff608d
(cherry picked from commit 3e035ebb726167aef43c4a865c7e7f7d3b0978fb)

subject: Correct revocation event test for domain_id

commit_message:
Correct revocation event test for domain_id

The revocation event test used "user_domain_id" and
"project_domain_id" as token fields that the "domain_id"
revocation event field maps to, but the token fields are
actually "identity_domain_id" and "assignment_domain_id", as
can be seen in
keystone.contrib.revoke.model.build_token_values().

Conflicts:

	keystone/tests/test_revoke.py

Change-Id: I208484da243403287eaa33893d57429c7e6d27c7
Partial-Bug: #1349597
(cherry picked from commit c4447f16da036fe878382ce4e1b05b84bdcc4d4e)

commit_message:
Fix for V2 token issued_at time changing

When the server converted a V2 token to a V3 token it regenerated
the issued_at time.

This was causing the server to return a different issued_at time
when a V2 token was validated using the V3 API.

This was causing the server to fail to revoke a V2 token if it was
revoked before validating it first because the regenerated token was
considered to be after the revocation event.

Change-Id: I71fea3253295ee8794fb2c8211e1f030de3ae205
Closes-Bug: #1348820
(cherry picked from commit a4c73e4382cb062aa9f30fe1960d5014d3c49cc2)

commit_message:
Add tests related to V2 token issued_at time changing

There was no test that showed that when a V2 token is used in a V3
context its "issued_at" time changes. This affects validating a V2
token using V3 and also revoking a V2 token. The tests show the
current incorrect behavior.

Partial-Bug: #1348820

Change-Id: I2a3443847b2699384413933ae164fdc183aa110f

commit_message:
Deprecate scheduler prep_resize

Scheduler prep_resize is no longer necessary as now the retries
from compute are going to the conductor.
Deprecating this method is also a prerequisite for the split
of the scheduler as it was issuing calls to computes.

Change-Id: I1092bbf7f541bb8cd7e33317f33b8c02761f284e

been moved to the keystonemiddleware repo.

commit_message:
Replace skipTest in favor of decorator

Within the dogtag tests, skipTest was used in each test case if the
import was not possible. Instead, this commit introduces the skip
decorator, so the whole class can be skipped, thus, reducing the
verbosity that had been introduced by the previous approach.

Change-Id: I86eb49e0371bc814f895299ede6a5816176fd135

subject: New manifest file to install/deploy Cisco N1KV-VEM module on compute nodes. A background on 'N1KV-VEM: It is the host-side component of N1KV implementing the notion of Virtual Ports for VM Interfaces and also handling the VM data-traffic. VEM is implemented as a couple of user-space processes and also has a KLM for efficient data-path switching. VEM manifests include: setting up the Config-File for VEM service, Starting VEM service and finally adding physical ports (along with port-profile) to the VEM

New manifest file to install/deploy Cisco N1KV-VEM module on compute nodes. [{'created': '2014-08-05 19:30:10.000000000', 'message': "guestagent/test_volume.py leaves a file in /tmp

Since the test mocks() execute and then calls write_to_fstab(), the
file created in /tmp by write_to_fstab() stays around. This is because
write_to_fstab() uses execute to remove the file. Replaced it with an
os.remove() and fixed the test which was counting two calls to
execute().

I'm fixing it because testing for another bug involves running tox
over and over again and leaving these files in /tmp is just a bit
messy.

Change-Id: Ia9e01049687644abd0671a658dffbbdcb4fba4bd
Closes-Bug: #1353064
"}]
commit_message:
guestagent/test_volume.py leaves a file in /tmp

Since the test mocks() execute and then calls write_to_fstab(), the
file created in /tmp by write_to_fstab() stays around. This is because
write_to_fstab() uses execute to remove the file. Replaced it with an
os.remove() and fixed the test which was counting two calls to
execute().

I'm fixing it because testing for another bug involves running tox
over and over again and leaving these files in /tmp is just a bit
messy.

Change-Id: Ia9e01049687644abd0671a658dffbbdcb4fba4bd
Closes-Bug: #1353064

To do that what I looked at the calls that updated or deleted an object AND also had a join in them to one of the exclusive locked objects that was pointed out earlier.  

I'll fully admit that identifying these isn't my strong suit :)"}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-08-05 15:45:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Add retry_on_deadlock to db update methods

There's some known races that have been addressed in
Nova via a retry_on_deadlock deocrator.  Some known
cases in Cinder exist as well when dealing with updates
to quotas and reservations_expire.

This patch introduces the decorator to Cinder and hits
the methods known to be susceptible to deadlock as well
as some others that seem as though they'd fall into the
same category.

Leverages work that's already been done in Nova

Co-Authored-By: Vish Ishaya <vishvananda@gmail.com>

Change-Id: Ic807f4f8a333e4d5477f86e41eea40191637087c
Partial-bug: #1350466

http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2014-04-07 16:54:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(4 inline comments)

I feel very strongly this is the wrong direction.

It is not clear to me what problems you are trying to solve.

If we want to move towards the conductor making the resource claims, it would be much better to add an RPC API to call down to the compute node to make the claims.

I feel we don't need this centralisation for the conductor to work, the conductor can make RPC API calls to the compute node to make the required reservations.

This is the "two phase" commit approach we may want to implement for the other reasons.

Now long term we might want to go this route, but I just can't see any justification for this move right now. This is a risk change, and I feel we should use our review bandwidth on bug fixes instead of this speculative architectural change. If the above calls from conductor to compute turn out not to work well, then we can look again at this approach.

I am -2 because I feel very strongly this should not get merged in its current state. Its not "this can never happen", its just a "please talk to me and get me to understand why we should do this".

I hope that makes sense.'}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2014-04-29 20:20:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

I'm going to ignore the details of the blueprint here and make a case for why I think resource claims should be persisted.  But I also now realize that it's also a case for splitting the resource tracker a bit.

yunhong-jiang explains that the resource tracker has three roles.  The second and third roles involve sending update data to the scheduler (technically the db the scheduler uses) that it can use for it's decisions.  The first case involves making claims for an instance.  I believe that the first case should be split out, and that these claims should be persisted.

If we want to get to a two phase commit process we're going to need to be able to lookup and act on these claims.  And we won't want them to disappear on a restart.  There's no guarantee that they can be rebuilt because there may not be an instance on the compute to match every claim made.

Furthermore, I think that RPC messages to compute nodes is a bit heavyweight for resource claims, but I don't have a strong position on this at the moment.  I think this also leads down the path of separating our data pathways a bit which is a good discussion but far outside the scope of this blueprint.

So in summary I think there's value in this proposal but it goes a bit further than perhaps it should right now."}, {'account_id': 4573, 'date': '2014-04-29 22:03:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

To Andrew's comment about rebuilding claims: I think that eludes to complications involved here. Is a claim becoming a first class entity that has to be managed independently of anything actually using the resources? That is not what it is at the moment, so I think its a more fundamental shift.

In many ways I like what you are proposing for the resource tracker, but it has far deeper than I think it should without more thorough design."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-02 09:58:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 4573, 'date': '2014-06-25 18:27:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17:

Hi, Paul, I think the only difference of cached claim and persistent claim is for compute restart. And I think it will be important to support the compute restart, considering: a) if we will support two-phase claim, i.e. someone can simply claim some resource, but w/o assign it to any instance/migration. We can't achieve it w/o persistent, b) The unique id. If we only cache claim, after restart, the id for the claims will be lost, this will cause confusing to consumer like user.

How do you think about it?"}, {'account_id': 4573, 'date': '2014-06-25 18:29:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 19.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-25 18:29:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19:

@Paul: I think the real benefit isn't in persisting the claim, though that's beneficial as well, but in being able to offer a claim ticket to a remote host.  Pretty much the only reason that prep_resize has to run on a compute is to make a resource tracker claim.  In order to ever realistically offer "simultaneous" scheduling it will need to claim resources as it goes.  And if we're going to offer claims remotely it would be nice if they weren't subject to disappearing due to a service restart.'}, {'account_id': 7166, 'date': '2014-06-26 07:11:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 19: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

Just a few clarifications asked, even if I'm OK with the overall direction. I'm not that fond of creating a local storage for claims, but go for it."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2014-06-26 08:09:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

I agree with some of the nits here, but I would like to see this move forward.

Feel free to put up patches to fix up some of those nits, if you want to address those issues, I am cool with that approach here.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-26 08:09:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19: -Verified

I have a few concerns with this spec:

* The problem statement is confusing, and its hard to see how the spec addresses the problem

* I am all for supporting remote claims, but I don't think we should be adding in persistant claims yet (if at all).
* nova should not assume that claims will always work they can fail for any number of reasons (including a nova-compute restart).

I would rather focus efforts on supporting remote claims that we may sometimes fail, and then addressing the specific case of a nova-compute restart after. We may find that restarts during a resource claim are infrequent enough that its not worth adding local persistant storage (yet another thing to debug)."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-08-04 22:36:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 19:

(3 comments)

Unfortunately, I did not get a chance to review this spec before it was approved... and I'm not all that thrilled with the implementation proposed, frankly.

I'm really not excited about putting a SQLite database on the compute node itself -- especially now that we just went through the effort to get rid of all DB calls in the no-db-compute efforts.

I thought that this spec was actually about serializing the claim object and allowing it to be passed back to the conductor, which could then call claim abort() in the event of a failure in one of the distributed steps of actions like migrate...

-jay"}, {'account_id': 4573, 'date': '2014-08-06 23:28:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19:

(3 comments)'}]

commit_message:
Persistent resource claim

This blueprint plans to enhance the compute resource tracker to provide
remote resource claim and track these claims persistently.

blueprint persistent-resource-claim

Change-Id: I437f7f4e3afce8195f4132fe8220d3e25903be19

Use oslosphinx to generate documentation

Rather than host different and possibly out of date versions of
static and theme files, use oslosphinx to generate the docs.

Change-Id: I7eadc8e40aa10cc26cfd6aece6efa5d13fee70b0

[{'created': '2014-06-26 08:48:18.000000000', 'message': 'Restore resource_id from backup_stack

When UpdateReplace is occured, the resource is moved to backup_stack,
and create new one. Then, resources which has dependency for updated
resource will be moved to backup_stack.

If the creation of update is interrupted by some reason(e.g. heat-engine
down), dependencies between backup_stack and exist_stack will exist.

Heat deletes backup_stack before deleting exist_stack. The dependency
still exists, so it will be failed. Thus, add behavior that restores
resource_id in the backup_stack when the stack is deleted.

commit_message:
Restore resource_id from backup_stack

When UpdateReplace is occurred, the resource is moved to backup_stack,
and create new one. Then, resources which has dependency for updated
resource will be moved to backup_stack.

If the creation of update is interrupted by some reason(e.g. heat-engine
down), dependencies between backup_stack and exist_stack will exist.

Heat deletes backup_stack before deleting exist_stack. The dependency
still exists, so it will be failed. Thus, add behavior that restores
resource_id in the backup_stack when the stack is deleted.

Change-Id: I32cecba17ae160d4631fb2611e34b91bb921dc5e
Closes-bug: #1334514

commit_message:
LaunchConfiguration replace on changed Metadata

This makes AWS::AutoScaling::LaunchConfiguration raise
an UpdateReplace if its template Metadata is changed on a
stack update. Any changes to LaunchConfiguration should result
in the resource being replaced, since this is how those changes
propagate to the scaling group.

This fixes a regression which has likely existed since
update_allowed_keys was removed: I78494aba07b6badeca8e95f1875ca8e4b9b0290c

Change-Id: I3a53422ed862777dffb9cac28088fbfe8dd417fa
Closes-Bug: #1287953

[{'created': '2014-07-24 15:16:54.000000000', 'message': 'Fix baremetal rescheduling errors

When using the Nova baremetal driver if you hit a condition
that causes a RescheduleException it will currently fail
if instance.node has not been set. This is because
the compute drivers macs_for_instance function is not
expected to throw exceptions in this case.

This patch updates the Nova BM compute driver such that it behaves
according to the documented driver interface thus giving us
a shot at rescheduling.

Closes-bug #1346424

Change-Id: Icbbe16ffef69132177165d21c727d791b62a232f

commit_message:
Revert "Deallocate the network if rescheduling for

Revert "Deallocate the network if rescheduling for Ironic"

This reverts commit 963ad71af4750e28745b6de262da11816b403801.

The original fix, targeted towards Nova BM and Ironic tests
is actually making us have more test failures. Lets go
back to the original race... and then we can have a bit
more time to test a proper fix.

Closes-bug #1346424

Change-Id: Icbbe16ffef69132177165d21c727d791b62a232f

commit_message:
Use guestagent conf set up by devstack

Devstack now sets up the trove-guestagent.conf in /etc/trove, so
we can (and should) just use that instead of copying the sample
guestagent conf over.

Change-Id: Ieab67ac29adef9929795cc5ffa1bc829bd07c422
Closes-bug: 1336090

commit_message:
Normalize Gemfile & pin tests to rspec < 2.99

Pin to rspec < 2.99 until rspec-puppet officially supports rspec 3.x.
This is to avoid warnings due to deprecated matchers in the
rspec-puppet gem.

This change is also intended to normalize the Gemfile for all stackforge
puppet modules.  This should facilitate pinning gem versions when
releasing new stable branches, since the same diff can be used for all
repos.

Conflicts:
  Gemfile

Change-Id: I8870d6cb3a1a895aac53ec3c096c413a52d02d19
Partial-Bug: #1326034
(cherry picked from commit 2553e6d1b26b137abdb979350257991fe93b3b24)

Updates documentation for lbaas-api-and-objmodel-improvement

(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89903/1)
Adds/updates code samples for Neutron LBaas API v2.0
Fixed formatting in JSON code samples
Updated os-lbaas-ext.wadl file
Updated method names to be more meaningful
Deleted the unused file:os-lbaas-ext-origional.wadl
Listener parameters added properly
Removed unused code samples
Corrected the discrepancies according to the updated google doc
Edits for consistency and clarity (DF)

Change-Id: I5a0f4eae1ae7dec4478bc06298c89ceee0553334
Closes-Bug: #1331525

commit_message:
Do not run Grenade steps for absent services

Users may wish to run Grenade against deployments with some optional services
disabled.  This adds some checks to is_service_enabled at various spots to
skip certain scripts if non-required services are disabled.

Change-Id: Ia2959adc71d67028d22e241bf90bc754a3000145

I'm looking for reasons why this won't build, and apparently there's a simpara being inserted at build time. I guess from a namespace switch possibly? 
More eyes would be great, as I can't see the problem for myself.

Here's what I know:
using 2.1.2 maven plugin
using 0.17 openstack-doc-tools dependency

mvn clean generate-sources works for just api-ref
tox -echeckbuild gives the errors we're seeing here on this patch, because it builds both api-ref and api-ref-guides and gets this:

<simpara><emphasis role="bold">Normal response codes: </emphasis><returnvalue>202</returnvalue></simpara><simpara><emphasis role="bold">Error response codes: </emphasis>computeFault (<errorcode>400</errorcode>, <returnvalue>500</returnvalue>, <returnvalue></returnvalue>),
            UnprocessableEntity (<errorcode>422</errorcode>),
            serviceUnavailable (<errorcode>503</errorcode>),
            badRequest (<errorcode>400</errorcode>),
            unauthorized (<errorcode>401</errorcode>),
            forbidden (<errorcode>403</errorcode>),
            badMethod (<errorcode>405</errorcode>),
            overLimit (<errorcode>413</errorcode>),
            itemNotFound (<errorcode>404</errorcode>),
            badMediaType (<errorcode>415</errorcode>),

commit_message:
template to rely on the the "id" attribute

The exception fixed is the following:
NoReverseMatch: Reverse for 'detail' with arguments '('',)' and keyword
arguments '{}' not found. 1 pattern(s) tried:
[u'project/volumes/(?P<volume_id>[^/]+)/$']

The test data doesn't include a volumeId attribute to volumes but they
contain an id attribute.

Here I modify the template to rely on the the "id" attribute but maybe
real data has a volumeId attribute and it's the test data in
openstack_dashboard/test/test_data/nova_data.py that needs to be
modified instead.

Change-Id: Ia561c2db1c59e51fb669e1ad6636d9b3bc9f7676

commit_message:
Fix FloatingIP.save() passing FixedIP object to sqlalchemy

This prevents the FloatingIP.save() method from passing the
calculated FixedIP object to the sqlalchemy floating_ip_update()
function, which would expect it to be an SA object. It also
aborts any attempt to save the object with a modified fixed_ip_id
linkage, as associate/disassociate should be used for that.

This also fixes a bug where FloatingIP expects the result of
floating_ip_update() to be a FloatingIp SA object.

Change-Id: I065caedf4d81c8583a3b390934a1d403cf2e87bd
Closes-bug: #1334164

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-05-08 20:52:18.000000000', 'message': 'Change neutron-ovs-agent to use ml2_conf.ini

This change allows the neutron-openvswitch-agent to use the
new ml2_conf.ini instead of the ovs_neutron_plugin.ini.

Change-Id: Iabfd8a33d58d4f45de24310211829cedbae001dd
'}, {'created': '2014-08-01 20:07:46.000000000', 'message': 'Use ml2_confi.ini in neutron-openvswitch-agent

This change switches the neutron-openvswitch-agent service to use the
ml2_conf.ini configuration file instead of ovs_neutron_plugin.ini.

Some required options were missing from the ml2_conf.ini template, so
those have been added.  The template for ovs_neutron_plugin.ini has been

commit_message:
Use ml2_conf.ini in neutron-openvswitch-agent

This change switches the neutron-openvswitch-agent service to use the
ml2_conf.ini configuration file instead of ovs_neutron_plugin.ini.

Some required options were missing from the ml2_conf.ini template, so
those have been added.  The template for ovs_neutron_plugin.ini has been
removed since it is no longer used.

Co-authored by: James Slagle <jslagle@redhat.com>
Change-Id: Iabfd8a33d58d4f45de24310211829cedbae001dd

Obscure IntegrityError message for plan-delete

Catches InternalServerError, looks for IntegrityError,
and returns an ideally more helpful message to the user.

[{'created': '2014-05-31 22:31:58.000000000', 'message': "Remove `with_lockmode` use from Trust SQL backend.

Due to the lack of support of `SELECT .. FOR UPDATE` call in
MySQL + Galera, the use of `with_lockmode('update')` needs to be
removed from the Trust SQL backend when utilizing the MySQL
dialect. This change is haneled with an extra column for
MySQL to leverage for locking the row in a separate transaction.

The lock is performed within a context manager to ensure cleanup
after the limited use trust updates the remaining consumptions.

SQL Migration 045 has been updated so that this can be backported
to Icehouse using one of the placeholder migrations.

SQL Migration 051 should be idempotent and make no changes if 045
with the update was previously applied.

Migration downgrades will only occur when downgrading below 045.

Due to the lack of support of `SELECT .. FOR UPDATE` call in
MySQL + Galera, the use of `with_lockmode('update')` needs to be
removed from the Trust SQL backend when utilizing the MySQL
dialect.

Instead of the pessimistic locking method (row lock, table lock),
use optimistic locking. The consume_use method now attempts to
update the remaining_uses column for the trust in question only
if the remaining_uses equal the same number as on the initial
query. This is done in a loop with a 10-iteration failsafe to
prevent endless looping.

Change-Id: I1b8af6ce5709f829f345cd351ec9242d0217e743

commit_message:
Remove `with_lockmode` use from Trust SQL backend.

Due to the lack of support of `SELECT .. FOR UPDATE` call in
MySQL + Galera, the use of `with_lockmode('update')` needs to be
removed from the Trust SQL backend when utilizing the MySQL
dialect.

Instead of the pessimistic locking method (row lock, table lock),
use optimistic locking. The consume_use method now attempts to
update the remaining_uses column for the trust in question only
if the remaining_uses equal the same number as on the initial
query. This is done in a loop with a 10-iteration failsafe to
prevent endless looping.

Change-Id: I1b8af6ce5709f829f345cd351ec9242d0217e743
Closes-Bug: #1325143

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but tempest unittests don't currently
pass a with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Change-Id: Ib54364877a251db48c54dfdc43c503281ea1f04a

commit_message:
Fix tab show/shown handlers for bootstrap v3

Also remove preventDefault() call from tab 'show' handler -
with that call it required 2 clicks to switch to a
lazy-loaded tab.

Change-Id: I4ba55c6f750cb9724287d5a9f2297666c0cece01
Closes-Bug: #1347002
Closes-Bug: #1350117

I took a closer look at quota.py and I realized something.  Quoting from the docstring of the CountableResource.__init__() method:

    Note that this counting is not performed in a transaction-safe
    manner.  This resource class is a temporary measure to provide
    required functionality, until a better approach to solving
    this problem can be evolved.

The original bugwhich gave rise to my comments about having some sort of check as to which method can be called with which resourceis a direct extension of this observation.  I had suggested in the email thread that CountableResource should be called with .reserve(), but the docstring indicates that it clearly should be called with .limit_check().

That said, your patch is still correct (see inline for the -1; just a minor redundancy I hadn't noticed before); it will enforce that CountableResource is called with .limit_check() only, which is correct.  We will need to open a bug against CountableResource to turn it into a reservable-type resource, however, which will probably not be easy."}, {'account_id': 6062, 'date': '2014-08-06 03:42:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Add valid method check for quota resources

ReservableResource and CountableResource comes down to
the method used to count the in-use
resources.  For ReservableResource, the count is based on the number of
database objects matching the project ID, whereas with
CountableResource, a counting function has to be specified; otherwise,
the classes are identical and designed to be used identically.indeed,
CountableResource extends ReservableResource and only overrides the
constructor.

This patch add some sanity-checking to limit_check() and
reserve() that ensure that they only work with the correct resource
type(s)

Change-Id: Ibec048a5d8c2c4a8685f5f3cc2076c64b39654a3
Partial-Bug: #1301532

commit_message:
Code to pass through transport_key_id when storing secret

This can happen in either a PUT or a GET request.  The
SecretStorePluginManager must return the plugin corresponding to
the transport_key_id, and must pass the transport_key as part
of the SecretDTO, so that the plugin will know the contents are
encrypted.

Implements: blueprint add-wrapping-key-to-barbican-server
Change-Id: Ieaa2bb7881cd34bcd891764945ef3c159062d4d4

replace dict.iteritems() with six.iteritems(dict)

should be replaced with six.iteritems(dict).

[{'created': '2014-07-29 13:59:04.000000000', 'message': "Move elements from ubuntu-guest to mysql and percona

The files 20-apparmor-mysql-local and 50-percona-server which were in
the ubuntu-guest element are only relevant for mysql and percona guest
agents and therefore having them in ubuntu-guest is not ideal. While
not catastrophic, it does mean that these settings show up in all
guest images.

The files have been relocated to ubuntu-mysql and ubuntu-percona and
renamed to keep the right sequence of execution and an update of

this is now occuring in the install.d phase of mysql (earlier it was
happening in pre-install of ubuntu-guest so the forced update wasn't
required).

commit_message:
Move elements from ubuntu-guest to mysql and percona

The files 20-apparmor-mysql-local and 50-percona-server which were in
the ubuntu-guest element are only relevant for mysql and percona guest
agents and therefore having them in ubuntu-guest is not ideal. While
not catastrophic, it does mean that these settings show up in all
guest images.

The files have been relocated to ubuntu-mysql and ubuntu-percona. The
file that adds the percona key has been put in a newly created
pre-install.d directory and renamed. The other (apparmor) has
similarly been moved into this new pre-install.d directory.

Change-Id: I6e8fd0fde37ee9689b9f6a669a33d579b2ba6c64
Closes-Bug: #1349553

commit_message:
xenapi: Do not retry snapshot upload on 500

If Glance returns a 500 response on an initial attempt to upload
a snapshot image, it will set the image status to killed.  Any retry
attempts will fail with a 409 response.

Hence, Nova should not attempt to retry the upload in this case, which
will eliminate many pointless retries.

Closes-Bug: 1349933

Change-Id: I1a8f2416923a368b02cf8963c747ebbb24d749a1

(12 comments)

Thanks for the review @Ruby...

About the async vs sync... I decided to go with sync (as it's in the spec) because:

 1- we already enforce a minimum interval between the ipmi  commands[1]

 2- For async stuff we would need a mechanism to allow the user to track the result of his request, for things like provision and power we have the target_* states but a target state for setting boot device IMO would be overkill. This can change this behavior once we start the work to have a fully async API in Ironic, then we are going to have some generic mechanism to allow set & tracking requests

commit_message:
Expose {set,get}_boot_device in the API

A new /nodes/<uuid>/management/boot_device subresource added exposing
ways to the client to {set,get} the boot device for a node.

* To set a boot device:

 PUT {'boot_device': 'pxe' } /nodes/<uuid>/management/boot_device[?persistent=<bool>]

* To get the current boot device:

 GET /nodes/<uuid>/management/boot_device[/supported]

 The /supported flag is used to list all the boot devices that is
 supported for that node.

Implements: blueprint new-management-interface
Change-Id: I7ab93b95112efb69cf7b2daab6bbd925cb2d1e02

commit_message:
Rename ironic-ilo-virtualmedia-deploy -> *-driver

The blueprint which is referenced by this spec is named
ironic-ilo-virtualmedia-driver. This name is correctly linked from
line 6 within the spec. However, the spec itself is misnamed.

This patch renames the spec file so that it matches the corresponding
blueprint.

Change-Id: I178be5cf55952e3ff674be121e19f2da3846eff5

commit_message:
Fixes and cleanups for missing lables

* Moved release notes to other pdf files. Building them as
  a separate job is not only pointless but also doesn't
  allow referencing other chapters with :ref tag from the
  release notes.

* Cleaned some broken references and labels.

Change-Id: I8029b6e165450214c01113818a29d9102a53cd30

http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2014-08-05 18:46:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Cindy, are we not using any mvc framework for rendering
html? mixing html and python is very problematic.'}, {'account_id': 6230, 'date': '2014-08-05 19:14:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1 Workflow+1

The MVC for horizon server side is... Django.
In this case you would move HTML to a template and then have the widget apply the template to generate HTML.

Django's widgets all have embedded HTML in strings as is done in monasca-ui. So I would recommend following this approach.

I will wait for more discussion before +2. Sounded like tongli was looking for another opinion from someone else."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-05 19:31:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

You raise a valid point litong01 while the django precedent of including html in python does not justify continuing this pattern. commit_message:
Simple refactor to stop passing around an unused parameter

There is no functional change in this patch.  However, this refactor
allows another patch [1] to make a simpler change to the code base.

This patch includes localizing the initialization of "internal_cidrs"
to a later spot in the "process_router" method.  This has the
advantage that it will be initialized under the same condition that it
will be used.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/109776

Change-Id: I3ca993d0a33b7c925526099e97999c9d9f76efc2

commit_message:
Fixed dependency on trove for int-tests

Cleaned up int-test dependencies so that the core int-test groups
are now registered entirely from trove python module. This enables
adding new int-tests for features in trove without creating a cross
repository dependency in trove-integration.

Change-Id: I13fad1179ea6d576d5b96592c8bf927037f51e7b
Closes-bug: 1343584

commit_message:
Fix spaceships

Then collector returns nothing we will end up with
null Class evaluation error. To fix it, use if defined().

Closes-bug: #1353340

Change-Id: Ic329bdd6ae7c91ef693263f5b84d1f0910ca962b
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Add ability to disable ceilometer-collector without db

You are no longer required to include ceilometer::db when
disabling ceilometer-collector using the enabled parameter.

The relationships with any database resources are now only enforced
when the service is enabled.

Closes-bug: #1352958
Change-Id: I00a5e651184788acdd30de1908e2bf38566f78e1

commit_message:
Make sure L3 agent uses the latest RPC version

Previously the base RPC version was set to 1.0
even though both server and agent are currently
at version 1.1, as for the L3 RPC API's are
concerned.

Closes-bug: #1339184

Change-Id: Ic33cc090ce22514e8c4dce64e2fb7c6a11c480a7

commit_message:
iLO Virtual Media iSCSI Deploy Driver

Add ability to provision proliant baremetal nodes (having iLO4 and
beyond) by booting the baremetal node with virtual media and
using iscsi from conductor node to deploy the image (reusing
existing deploy mechanism).

Change-Id: Ib01518dda95b3bfb650c4eb469a9355311bfab02

commit_message:
Fix unexpected return from Step::__init__()

The __init__() method should always returns None, this patch fix a unexpected
return statement with a TypeError exception, which should be corrected to a
raise statement.

Change-Id: I96d081ab23ac499d6151161d1ae59864c78ea44e
Closes-Bug: 1353270

commit_message:
Remove old DLO config remenents from proxy

Config items 'rate_limit_after_segment' and
'rate_limit_segments_per_sec' are configuration items left over from
before DLO was moved from the proxy server and into it's own
middleware. This change removes the configuration options from the
proxy server.

Change-Id: Ie3d42a57cda813feed019f01db986f13cdff9c31

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-04 06:14:17.000000000', 'message': "Swift configuration parameter audit

NOTE:
  This is my first pass of the configuration audit. At this point
  in time I want people to look at it, but _not_ merge it yet. As
  I want people to look, I wont set it as WIP as that will mean
  reviewers will skip over it.

  This change is based of a comparison of the sample configurations
  and the swift code. After this, I will compare the documentation
  and update as required.

This change is the result of an audit through the config parameters
provided by swift and how/if they are addressed in the swift
documentation. The documentation being the sample config files in
the /etc directory or the documentation.

This change makes the following assumptions:
  - Unless stated otherwise, the commented out parameter in the
    sample configuration is the default for swift.

  - When the default in the code differs from that of the sample
    configuration, the default in the code is correct.

Container reconciler:
  Parameter: interval
    - code: 30
    - config: 300
  Result: config = 30

Object Expirer:
  Parameter: recon_cache_path
    - code: /var/cache/swift
    - config: Parameter missing
  Result: Add parameter

swift-dispersion-populate && swift-dispersion-report
  Parameter: auth_version
    - code: 1.0
    - config: 2.0
  Result: config = 1.0

swift-drive-audit:
  Parameter: log_file_pattern
    - code: /var/log/kern.*[!.][!g][!z]
    - config: /var/log/kern*
  Result: config = /var/log/kern.*[!.][!g][!z]

  NOTE: swift-drive-audit uses a parameter called device_dir which
        defaults to '/srv/node'. In all other swift binaries/services
        there is a similar parameter called devices which stores the
        same thing. This is an inconsistency which I haven't fixed
        as this could break existing swift clusters out in the wild.

Proxy Server:
  Parameter: object_chunk_size
    - code: 65536
    - config: 8192
  Result: config = 65536

  Parameter: client_chunk_size
    - code: 65536
    - config: 8192
  Result: config = 65536

  Parameter: rate_limit_segments_per_sec
    - code: 1
    - config: 0
  Result: config = 1
  NOTE: '0' means no rate limiting.

  Parameter: strict_cors_mode
    - code: True
    - config: No parameter
  Result: config = True

Account and Container replicator configuration confusion:
  NOTES:
    The account and container replicators have parameters:
      - interval
      - run_pause

    Both of these are loaded into the same variable in code:
      self.interval = int(conf.get('interval') or
                          conf.get('run_pause') or 30)

    If a user sets both to different values then interval is used.
  Result: Update the configuration to make this more clear.

Change-Id: Iaadbb1a6284f8b3e0801bc343b29772f70f4bf6e

          default and make the sample configuration for auth version
          2.0 easier to understand.

swift-drive-audit:
  Parameter: log_file_pattern
    - code: /var/log/kern.*[!.][!g][!z]
    - config: /var/log/kern*
  Result: config = /var/log/kern.*[!.][!g][!z]

  NOTE: swift-drive-audit uses a parameter called device_dir which
        defaults to '/srv/node'. In all other swift binaries/services
        there is a similar parameter called devices which stores the
        same thing. This is an inconsistency which I haven't fixed
        as this could break existing swift clusters out in the wild.

  Parameter: object_chunk_size
    - code: 65536

  Parameter: strict_cors_mode
    - code: True

  Result: config = True

Account and Container replicator configuration confusion:
  NOTES:
    The account and container replicators have parameters:

      self.interval = int(conf.get('interval') or
                          conf.get('run_pause') or 30)

    If a user sets both to different values then interval is used.
  Result: Update the configuration to make this more clear.

commit_message:
Swift configuration parameter audit

This change is the result of an audit through the config parameters
provided by swift and how/if they are addressed in the swift
documentation. The documentation being the sample config files in
the /etc directory or the documentation.

This change is only concerned with the config files in etc/ next
I will look at the documentation in the doc/ folder.

This change makes the following assumptions:
  - Unless stated otherwise, the commented out parameter in the
    sample configuration is the default for swift.

  - When the default in the code differs from that of the sample
    configuration, the default in the code is correct.

Container reconciler:
  Parameter: interval
    - code: 30
    - config: 300
  Result: config = 30

Object Expirer:
  Parameter: recon_cache_path
    - code: /var/cache/swift
    - config: Parameter missing
  Result: Add parameter

swift-dispersion-populate && swift-dispersion-report
  Parameter: auth_version
    - code: 1.0
    - config: 2.0 (due to being a confusing example of how to setup
                   version 2.0).
  Result: Added 'auth_version = 1.0' to the right section (showing
          default and make the sample configuration for auth version
          2.0 easier to understand.

swift-drive-audit:
  Parameter: log_file_pattern
    - code: /var/log/kern.*[!.][!g][!z]
    - config: /var/log/kern*
  Result: config = /var/log/kern.*[!.][!g][!z]

  NOTE: swift-drive-audit uses a parameter called device_dir which
        defaults to '/srv/node'. In all other swift binaries/services
        there is a similar parameter called devices which stores the
        same thing. This is an inconsistency which I haven't fixed
        as this could break existing swift clusters out in the wild.

Proxy Server:
  Parameter: object_chunk_size
    - code: 65536
    - config: 8192
  Result: config = 65536

  Parameter: client_chunk_size
    - code: 65536
    - config: 8192
  Result: config = 65536

  Parameter: strict_cors_mode
    - code: True
    - config: No parameter
  Result: config = True

Account and Container replicator configuration confusion:
  NOTES:
    The account and container replicators have parameters:
      - interval
      - run_pause

    Both of these are loaded into the same variable in code:
      self.interval = int(conf.get('interval') or
                          conf.get('run_pause') or 30)

    If a user sets both to different values then interval is used.
  Result: Update the configuration to make this more clear.

DocImpact
Change-Id: Iaadbb1a6284f8b3e0801bc343b29772f70f4bf6e

commit_message:
Check for tardiff and add site to README.

When I rad milestone.sh the first time, one error I hit was that I
didn't have tardiff installed (and obviously didn't read the prereqs
in the README).  Note where you can find tardiff in the README and
also check for tardiff to be available as a sanity check before using
it.

Change-Id: Iafcbd173d3cd06af5873686c38af5aa3bd780e16

commit_message:
Install default-jre from devstack script

Currently, if you don't have java installed congress will fail to start
this patch fixes this by having devstack install the jre for us.

Change-Id: I9bb8bde6aa99fb22998c18b157e2793f93f2e7ee
closes-bug: 1353132

commit_message:
Update to Twitter Bootstrap 3

- Update modal form template
- Update button css classes
- Update search button
- Update templates with the replacement
  class="span12" -> class="col-xs-12 col-sm-12 col-md-12 col-lg-12"

Closes-Bug: #1350894:

Change-Id: Id2924cc3427485c949a57b08779a4c3795613aa4

commit_message:
Spec for removing tenant-id from api resource uri

Patch 2:
  Added examples for couple additional use cases where
  the API could be called by an admin user on behalf of
  another user.
  Fixed spec based on previous review comments

Patch 3:
  Added a work item for policy change

Patch 4:
  Removed the special admin use cases based on review
  comments.
  Made text corrections based on feedback
  Update the work items and backward compatibility logic

Patch 5:
  Cleaned up formatting/work-items
  Changed X-Tenant-Id to X-Project-Id

Patch 6:
  More formatting fixes

Patch 7:
  Removed Backward Compatibility support
  Changed spec name to match blueprint

Patch 8:
  Replaced all occurences of tenant-id with project-id
  Fixed wording errors based on review comments

Patch 9:
  Included client changes as another work item

Change-Id: I76a5e80288aed42d2b73839a2132f6c3e2cbb3dd
Blueprint: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/barbican/+spec/api-remove-uri-tenant-id

commit_message:
Update oslo.rootwrap to 1.3.0.0a1

oslo.config 1.3.0.0a1 has the ChainingRegExpFilter which Cinder will
adopt to allow 'cgexec' and 'ionice' commands.

Change-Id: Idec4427e2757d1bdc54f48cfd871705827d6ba70

commit_message:
Add test skip decorator when service not available

Adding services_required decorator that can be used for decorating test classes
as well as test methods. Decorator expects as arguments services that
should be available during test execution.

Skipping decorators are not available in the nose python library,
therefore custom skipping decorator has to be made.

Partially implements blueprint: selenium-integration-testing

Change-Id: I6de4ec75ef9dc56f1ed11057d8b30bb0a782c6e3

commit_message:
Support external DHCP providers

This spec adds support for external DHCP providers to remove a hard
dependency on Neutron's DHCP server.

Change-Id: I1d27ad099a34dcf25e649925ba42ad3084a2b65e

commit_message:
Remove extra config block

This config block is entirely redundant and is actually causing an error
with the cinder passthrough config support. An extra "[]" is added to
the bottom of /etc/cinder/cinder.conf from the passthrough support
causing the following error from cinder-volume:

oslo.config.cfg.ConfigFileParseError: Failed to parse /etc/cinder/cinder.conf:
at /etc/cinder/cinder.conf:34, Empty section name: '[]'

Change-Id: Id9089b2fa37b8abd2f9d83087736e7fb7305210d

commit_message:
Cinder: allow customization of the iscsi helper

Updates devtest_overcloud.sh so that we can customize
the Cinder iscsi_helper option. The default is still
tgtadm.

This is important because it allows users of LIO to
automatically set their default iscsi_helper to
lioadm when using devtest. LIO is the preferred
default on Fedora and RHEL.

Change-Id: I9860f6b57a2f6632119ae2a23d997d12a767d0dd

If an invalid pool is specified when creating a floating ip
with neutron as the backend a FloatingIpPoolNotFound exception
can be raised. This change handles the exception at the API level.

Change-Id: Iac46d86a11f2c1da0ed7e7861cdb87fd4d4b4c6c
Closes-Bug: 1352141

commit_message:
Handle FloatingIpPoolNotFound exception in floating ip creation

If an invalid pool is specified when creating a floating ip
with neutron as the backend a FloatingIpPoolNotFound exception
can be raised. This change handles the exception at the API level.

Change-Id: Iac46d86a11f2c1da0ed7e7861cdb87fd4d4b4c6c
Closes-Bug: 1352141

commit_message:
Allow keepalived to load kernel modules

Toggle a SElinux boolean to allow keepalived to load kernel modules
when SELinux is in enforcing mode.

Closes-Bug: 1342872
Change-Id: I8b53ade65426c132e4200e0cbd6800ee9e59f00f

The issue is that the thing to call is called in a method that then raises and we catch the exception, so its hard to get at.

I think we should add a 'deallocate_network_on_reschedule' driver call, defaulted to False, and return True for that in the ironic and nova-baremetal drivers."}, {'account_id': 1030, 'date': '2014-07-24 13:32:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

My preference would be a new driver method/attribute which would just return a Boolean "should this be deallocated" as has been mentioned here.

The reason you're having node issues is that the object is updated in _build_and_run_instance but that mutation doesn't get passed back up to the calling scope.  So and instance.refresh would work at the expense of an additional db call.'}, {'account_id': 1030, 'date': '2014-07-24 13:54:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

instance.node could still be None if the claim failed... tho in this case, the network would not be allocated yet.  So you'd have to do:

  ....

ALthough the node check seems too specific for baremetal.  New driver method is the right way."}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2014-07-24 16:45:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Add method for deallocating networks on reschedule

The original call to dhcp_options_for_instance() is not a great way to
check whether deallocation of networks should happen on reschedules.

This adds a new virt driver method 'deallocate_networks_on_reschedule'
which can be used by a virt driver to say whether reschedules should
deallocate networks first. This defaults to False and modifies the
baremetal virt driver to return True. Ironic virt driver will also need
to return True.

Closes-Bug: 1342919
Change-Id: I54a3252ab15e2d8b596ccc90eb4755405021f1da

commit_message:
Add the arithmetic transformer endpoint to setup.cfg

The arithmetic transformer patch at
I1b637e5b1d1bb15ed3c3d7ec758d2a684eaccf21 did not
add the new transformer into the setup.cfg's endpoints, so
this patch does.

commit_message:
Enable haproxy_connect_any port access

Enable a boolean to allow haproxy to proxy any port. If not set,
SELinux, in enforcing mode, denies haproxy access and haproxy will
fail to start.

Closes-Bug: 1339938
Change-Id: Ic7980285d2aa678315d73295226508fcf2de40f8

commit_message:
Fixed DeprecationWarning in exc_filters

DeprecationWarning: BaseException.message has been deprecated as of Python 2.6
This warning was generated in exc_filters during exception conversions.
Fix it by removing access to deprecated attribute

Closes-Bug: #1257530

Change-Id: I8ff8b974946ecab13f12a70b315dd94c3453197e

commit_message:
Add network_device_mtu value to dnsmasq options file

Despite network_device_mtu option can be specified in
neutron.conf, its value is not applied to VMs.
Adding it to dnsmasq options file will force
dhcp server to pass the mtu value to VMs.

Also added a unit test.

Closes-Bug: 1348788
Change-Id: I8d673134746f13585b2672866a5feb6e254f93ae

commit_message:
Use my_ip for neutron URL

Currently, neutron URL is set 127.0.0.1 in ironic.conf.
This patch fix this using $my_ip same as other component's URL
(for example glance).

Change-Id: I558fccc74058fcc493cbf52799fe021b12518253

commit_message:
Change packages to monasca.thresh

The diffs are going to be very hard to read on this change, but
basically the change is from com.hpcloud.mon to monasca.thresh.

Since monasca-common packages haven't changed, yet, they are still
referenced as com.hpcloud.mon, but everything else has changed to
monasca.thresh.

The init script has also been changed to invoke the new package path.

Change-Id: I5aad9302a8f5b11ed1b9874160f0d7a9882c5b2d

Dividing this method into multiple helps to reuse it in
some tools scripts for generating data.

commit_message:
Fix make_test_data tools script

Method get_connection has been renamed to
get_connection_from_config.

Resource is object not dictionary, so attributes needs to be
accessed that way.

Change-Id: I19e09f3e9077d3346b4361fa6975a3e696e2e765
Related-Bug: #1349791

commit_message:
Use CentOS cmd while syncing time on bootstrap

If node in bootstrap mode we should use 'ntpd' as
daemon name wile synchronizing time, even if Ubuntu
is selected as OS, because bootstrap image is based
on CentOS.

Change-Id: I182c2796de5c5bed8e4b3fe67f63125f5e10c57f
Closes-bug: #1353455

commit_message:
first pass of integrating javelin2 to grenade

This provides support for creating users, images, servers, and
objects and checking on the far side.

Depends-On: If5f2674179eea4972ad43a1581073d483bb75d79 from
tempest to fix some javelin issues to make it usable.

Change-Id: I3634fd1c1db08a9a03e2dce56ebe5424fe2f27d5

Only upgrade the services that are actually active in grenade,
making it runnable outside of the gate environment where ceilometer
isn't enabled.

Ensure the /opt/stack directory can be built and owned by the stack
user.

Wait long enough for nova-compute to shut down, because otherwise
we'll often die there.

commit_message:
Only upgrade services we are actually running

Only upgrade the services that are actually active in grenade,
making it runnable outside of the gate environment where ceilometer
isn't enabled.

Change-Id: I3aeff82ceb99fbfa3689141f0dae974189c7370a

commit_message:
Fix issue with snapshot name on error

In patching tests, when error happens
identical snapshot names was used in case
of error, so we can not revert all errored envs.

Change-Id: I0d8bde7989f4bacaec728759b060bd53f9f17cf7

commit_message:
make grenade logdir creation work on clean system

On a completely fresh system, /opt/stack is something which doesn't
yet exist, and the directory creation for it will fail on the first
try. By reordering the directory creation it will be easier for
people to get this working with completely fresh systems.

Change-Id: I5183ce091d0c3d417e700aa2c8b932507e51c16a
